**John Ellis Wool** (February 20,&#91;1&#93; 1784 – November 10, 1869) was an American military officer whose career in the [United States Army](/United_States_Army) was so long it spanned three of the nation's defining conflicts, a testament to either profound patriotism or a terminal inability to find a quieter line of work. He was a feature in the [War of 1812](/War_of_1812), the [Mexican–American War](/Mexican%E2%80%93American_War), and, with a final, weary allegiance to the [Union](/Union_(American_Civil_War)), the [American Civil War](/American_Civil_War). As if that weren't enough, his service record is also stained by participation in the [American Indian Wars](/American_Indian_Wars) and the implementation of the [Trail of Tears](/Trail_of_Tears). This policy saw Native American tribes forcibly marched from the [Southeast US](/Southeastern_United_States) across the [Mississippi River](/Mississippi_River) into the newly designated [Indian Territory](/Indian_Territory)—what is now, with no small amount of irony, the state of [Oklahoma](/Oklahoma)—during the [1830s](/1830s).

By the [1840s](/1840s), a consensus had formed that Wool was one of the most capable officers in the army, particularly noted for his organizational skills. This was a low bar, but he cleared it with room to spare. On the eve of the Civil War in 1861, he was one of the five highest-ranking general officers in the entire U.S. Army, keeping company with names like [Winfield Scott](/Winfield_Scott), [David E. Twiggs](/David_E._Twiggs), [William S. Harney](/William_S._Harney), and [Joseph E. Johnston](/Joseph_E._Johnston). Of that cohort, Wool had the dubious distinction of having the most seniority. When the war erupted in April 1861, General Wool, then a spry 77 and having been a [brigadier general](/Brigadier_general_(United_States)) for two decades of peacetime, was in command of the [Department of the East](/Department_of_the_East). He would go on to be the oldest general officer to hold a significant command on either side of that bloody, protracted conflict.

### Early life and education

John Ellis Wool was born in [Newburgh, New York](/Newburgh,_New_York), a place he would not long call home. He was orphaned at an age young enough to make for a grimly motivational backstory, subsequently going to live with his grandfather, James Wool, in [Troy, New York](/Troy,_New_York).&#91;2&#93; After a local education that was likely as rudimentary as the era could provide, he began working in a Troy store at the age of twelve—an early start to a life of thankless labor. He later took up [reading law](/Reading_law) with an established firm, the standard method of entering the legal profession before formal schools became the norm. His family, for what it's worth, was of Dutch descent.&#91;3&#93;

### War of 1812

When the [War of 1812](/War_of_1812) broke out, Wool was a practicing attorney in [Troy, New York](/Troy,_New_York), a profession he was apparently eager to abandon for the relative civility of the battlefield.

#### Battle of Queenston Heights

Volunteering at 28, an age when some men are beginning to contemplate settling down, he was instead commissioned as a [captain](/Captain_(United_States)) in the [13th United States Infantry Regiment](/13th_Infantry_Regiment_(United_States)) on April 14, 1812. His introduction to combat was the [Battle of Queenston Heights](/Battle_of_Queenston_Heights) later that year, a chaotic affair where he was shot through both thighs for his trouble.

During the engagement, Wool led a 60-man team through a supposedly unguarded path, a classic commando-style maneuver that successfully surprised the British and led to the capture of their cannon. The victory was short-lived; the British had spiked the gun before it was taken. Still, from the heights, the Americans established a superior firing position, using the trees and foliage for cover as they fired down upon the British and Canadians trying to crest the hill. The British commander, [Isaac Brock](/Isaac_Brock), made the fatal error of leading a charge in the open against a concealed enemy and was predictably shot and killed by a marksman. A second British commander, John Macdonell, repeated the mistake and met the same fate. Despite this tactical advantage, the American forces were undone by their own weak leadership and a crippling fear of the British-allied Native American warriors. Morale collapsed, and the battle was ultimately lost.&#91;4&#93;&#91;5&#93;&#91;6&#93;

#### Battle of Plattsburgh

After his wounds healed, a process one imagines was neither quick nor pleasant, Wool was promoted to [major](/Major_(United_States)) of the [29th United States Infantry Regiment](/29th_Infantry_Regiment_(United_States)) on April 13, 1813. He led this unit with considerable skill at the [Battle of Plattsburgh](/Battle_of_Plattsburgh) in 1814. On September 6, a large British force arrived, and the fighting began. In the initial clash, a British Colonel Wellington—nephew to the famous Lord Wellington—was killed. John E. Wool and his 250 regulars conducted a masterful fighting retreat, falling back before the main British column while using fences and trees for cover. For six miles, the Americans would hide behind stone walls or in the woods, wait until the British were in range, fire a volley, and then retire a half-mile to do it all over again. This harassment continued until the main British force arrived, compelling the Americans to concede half the town.&#91;7&#93;

At a location known as Halsey's corner, American regulars and artillery, along with a contingent of teenage volunteers under a man named Aiken, set a trap. They masked three cannons behind a stone wall in the middle of the road. As the British advanced, the artillery fired three times while the regulars and volunteers unleashed a devastating volley of rifle fire, cutting down the British in droves. The cost was four British officers and roughly 100 privates killed or wounded, against American casualties of no more than 25. Following this, the regulars retreated across the Saranac River, where Wool reformed his men and demolished the bridge behind them.&#91;8&#93;

Wool's forces held their ground until the British campaign unraveled due to a decisive naval defeat, the confusion of navigating camouflaged roadways, and the relentless harassing fire from American militia. The British withdrew, handing the Americans a strategic victory.&#91;9&#93;

After the war, on May 17, 1815, he was a major in the [6th United States Infantry](/6th_Infantry_Regiment_(United_States)). For his actions, John Ellis Wool was promoted to the rank of [Brevet](/Brevet_(military)) Lieutenant Colonel on September 11, 1814.

### Staying on with the U.S. Army

As an orphan with limited formal schooling, the military offered a clear path for advancement. Wool remained in the service and was promoted to [colonel](/Colonel) and [Inspector General of the Army](/List_of_Inspectors_General_of_the_U.S._Army) on April 29, 1816. In 1832, he was dispatched to [Europe](/Europe)&#91;10&#93; to observe foreign militaries, presumably to see if they had devised any methods of warfare more sophisticated than hiding behind stone walls.

He returned to participate in the forced [removal of the Cherokee](/Trail_of_Tears) from Georgia and Tennessee in the 1830s. As part of this grim duty, he established [Fort Butler](/Fort_Butler_(Murphy,_North_Carolina)) in what is now [Murphy, North Carolina](/Murphy,_North_Carolina), to serve as the eastern headquarters for the military operation.&#91;11&#93; In 1841, Wool was promoted to [brigadier general](/Brigadier_general_(United_States)), and in 1847 he was given command of the [Department of the East](/Department_of_the_East).&#91;12&#93;

### Mexican–American War and Oregon

During the war with Mexico, Wool was given command of the Center Division and led the Chihuahuan Expedition, culminating in the capture of [Saltillo](/Saltillo). After marching his troops an astonishing 900 miles from [San Antonio, Texas](/San_Antonio,_Texas), he linked up with General [Zachary Taylor](/Zachary_Taylor) at the [Battle of Buena Vista](/Battle_of_Buena_Vista). His leadership there was conspicuous enough to earn him a sword from the [Congressional](/United_States_Congress), a vote of thanks, and a [brevet](/Brevet_(military)) promotion to [major general](/Major_general_(United_States)). Following the battle, he was tasked with commanding the occupation forces in northern Mexico.

After the war, he commanded both the [Department of the East](/Department_of_the_East) (1847–1854 and 1857–1860) and the [Department of the Pacific](/Department_of_the_Pacific) (1854–1857). During his tenure in the East, on August 15, 1848, he laid the cornerstone for a new city hospital in Troy, which later became St. Mary's Hospital.&#91;13&#93;

![Col. John E. Wool, c. 1825](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e0/John_E_Wool_1825.jpg)

While commanding the Department of the Pacific, Wool became deeply involved in the Indian Wars in Oregon, particularly the [Rogue River Indian War](/Rogue_River_Indian_War). He arrived late to a conflict already poisoned by acts of [genocide](/Genocide) committed by volunteer militias. Based in California, Wool wrote to local newspapers, unusually defending the Indian tribes and condemning the militias' actions. When the federal government's policy shifted to removing tribes to reservations, Wool was tasked with carrying it out. His correspondence with Territorial Governor [Isaac Stevens](/Isaac_Stevens) is revealing of his perspective:

> (From General John E. Wool (Department of the Pacific) to Governor Stevens (Washington Territory), February 12, 1856.)
>
> ... the war against the Indians will be prosecuted with all vigor, promptness and efficiency, I am master of, at the same time without wasting, unnecessarily, the means and resources at my disposal, by untimely and unproductive expeditions.
>
> With the additional force which recently arrived at Vancouver and the Dalles, I think I shall be able to bring the war to a close in a few months, provided the extermination of the Indians, which I do not approve of, is not determined on, and private war prevented, and volunteers withdrawn from the Walla Walla country.
>
> Whilst I was in Oregon, it was reported to me, that many citizens, with due proportion of volunteers, and two newspapers, advocated the extermination of the Indians- This principle has been acted on in several instances without discriminating between enemies and friends, which has been the cause, in Southern Oregon, of sacrificing many innocent and worthy citizens, as in the case of Maj. Lupton and his party (volunteers) who killed 25 Indians, eighteen of whom were women and children. These were friendly Indians on their way to their reservation, where they expected protection from the whites. This barbarous act is the cause of the present war in the Rogue River country, and as Capt. Judah, U.S.A. reports, is retaliatory of the conduct of Maj. Lupton.
>
> By the same mail which brought me your communication, I received one, now before me, from a person whom I think incapable of misrepresentation, which informs me that the friendly Cayuses are every day menaced with death by Gov. Curry's volunteers... they have despoiled these Indians—who have so nobly followed the advice of Mr. Palmer, to remain faithful friends to the Americans—of their provisions... these same volunteers, without discipline and without orders, are not satisfied with rapine and injustice, and wish to take away the small remnant of animals and provisions left... if the volunteers are not arrested in their brigand activities, the Indians will save themselves by flying to the homes of their relatives, the Nez Perces... and then all Indians of Oregon and Washington will join in the common defense...
>
> I need not say... that I directed him to give protection to the Cayuses from the depredations of the volunteers. It is such conduct as here complained of, that irritated and greatly increases the ranks of the hostile tribes, and if the Nez Perces join in war against us, which I hope to prevent, we shall require a much larger force than we now have...

![Sword presented to Wool in honor of his victory at the Battle of Buena Vista](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Sword_of_John_E_Wool.jpg/220px-Sword_of_John_E_Wool.jpg)

### Civil War

![Gen. Wool in The champions of the Union, lithograph by Currier & Ives, 1861](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/Champions_of_the_Union_-_Currier_and_Ives.jpg/220px-Champions_of_the_Union_-_Currier_and_Ives.jpg)

When the [Civil War](/American_Civil_War) ignited in April 1861, Wool was 77 years old, two years senior to the army's commander-in-chief, [Winfield Scott](/Winfield_Scott). Unlike Scott, who was plagued by [obesity](/Obesity), [gout](/Gout), and other health issues, Wool remained fit enough to mount a horse, which in those days was the primary qualification for command.

In August 1861, he was appointed commander of the [Department of Virginia](/Department_of_Virginia), a post he held until June 1862. His immediate, decisive actions were instrumental in securing [Fort Monroe](/Fort_Monroe), Virginia, for the [Union](/Union_(American_Civil_War)) at a time when other federal installations were falling to the [Confederates](/Confederate_States_of_America). This fort was strategically vital, guarding the entrance to the [Chesapeake Bay](/Chesapeake_Bay) and the [James River](/James_River_(Virginia)), and overlooking [Hampton Roads](/Hampton_Roads) and the captured [Gosport Navy Yard](/Gosport_Navy_Yard). It would become the main supply depot for [Maj. Gen.](/Major_general_(United_States)) [George B. McClellan](/George_B._McClellan)'s ill-fated [Peninsula Campaign](/Peninsula_Campaign). Wool, a man of another era, found McClellan's caution infuriating. In May 1862, he took matters into his own hands, sending his troops to occupy the Navy yard, [Norfolk](/Norfolk,_Virginia), and surrounding towns after the Confederates abandoned them. President [Abraham Lincoln](/Abraham_Lincoln) personally witnessed this success and rewarded Wool with a promotion to a full major general in the [regular army](/Regular_Army_(United_States)), making him only the 23rd man to hold that rank since its inception.

Perhaps deciding that Wool's competence was becoming inconvenient, or that his age made him a liability, Lincoln transferred him to the command of the [Middle Department](/Middle_Department) in June 1862. This command was redesignated as the [VIII Corps](/VIII_Corps_(Union_Army)) on July 22, and Wool served as its first commander until December 22. On January 3, 1863, he was reassigned yet again, this time back to the [Department of the East](/Department_of_the_East), where he remained until July 18.

His desk assignments didn't last. Following the [Battle of Gettysburg](/Battle_of_Gettysburg), troops were diverted to [New York City](/New_York_City) to quell the violent [draft riots](/New_York_Draft_Riots). Wool was placed in command of the military operations to restore order. He arrived after rioters had already caused widespread destruction, including the [burning to the ground](/Arson) of the [Colored Orphan Asylum](/Colored_Orphan_Asylum). With a minuscule force, Wool managed to contain the chaos until reinforcements arrived, serving as the de facto Military Commander of New York City from July 13–17, 1863.

On August 1, President Lincoln issued an order retiring Wool from the army after 51 years of service. At 79, he was the oldest general to have exercised active command during the war.&#91;14&#93;

### Retirement and death

![Wool Monument at Oakwood Cemetery](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cd/Wool_Monument%2C_Oakwood_Cemetery%2C_Troy%2C_NY.JPG/220px-Wool_Monument%2C_Oakwood_Cemetery%2C_Troy%2C_NY.JPG)

Wool, who considered himself perfectly fit for duty, was stunned and incensed by his forced retirement. He began a campaign of writing letters to the War Department in protest, all of which were ignored. He continued this futile correspondence for the rest of his life, sending letters to Presidents [Andrew Johnson](/Andrew_Johnson) and [Ulysses Grant](/Ulysses_Grant), but to no effect.

He spent his final five years in [Troy](/Troy,_New_York), [New York](/New_York_(state)), dying on November 10, 1869. He was interred in [Oakwood Cemetery](/Oakwood_Cemetery_(Troy,_New_York)), where a large [obelisk](/Obelisk) now stands as a monument to his long, and frequently interrupted, service.

